  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about zero forex markup credit cards</p></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">How much can I save with a zero forex markup card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Savings depend on your international spending volume. If you spend ₹1 lakh per year internationally (subscriptions, travel, online shopping), a regular card at 3.5% markup costs you ₹3,500 extra. A zero forex card saves you this entire amount. For heavy international spenders at ₹5 lakh per year, savings jump to ₹17,500 — more than enough to justify even a paid card's annual fee. Factor in that even a "low markup" 2% card still costs ₹2,000 per ₹1 lakh spent. Zero markup is zero — there's no more cost-effective way to transact internationally.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Do zero forex cards use the same exchange rate as regular cards?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, both zero forex and regular cards use the Visa or Mastercard interbank exchange rate for conversion. The only difference is the markup. Regular cards add 2-3.5% on top of the interbank rate, while zero forex cards add nothing. For example, if the interbank USD/INR rate is ₹83.50, a regular card charges ₹86.42 (at 3.5% markup) while a zero forex card charges exactly ₹83.50. The interbank rate itself is typically very competitive — much better than airport money changers or forex dealers.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Are there any hidden charges on zero forex cards?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Genuine zero forex markup cards have no hidden currency conversion charges. However, be aware of: (1) GST of 18% on the forex markup (which is zero, so GST is also zero), (2) TCS (Tax Collected at Source) of 20% on international card spending exceeding ₹7 lakh per financial year — this applies to all cards, not just zero forex ones, (3) Regular credit card charges like interest on revolving credit, late payment fees, etc. still apply. Always read the card's fee schedule carefully to understand all applicable charges beyond the forex markup.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can I use a zero forex card for recurring international subscriptions?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Absolutely. Zero forex cards work perfectly for recurring international subscriptions like Netflix (international plans), Spotify, Adobe Creative Cloud, Microsoft 365, AWS, ChatGPT Plus, YouTube Premium (if billed in USD), and any other service charging in foreign currency. The zero markup applies to every recurring transaction automatically. This is actually one of the best use cases for zero forex cards — even small monthly savings of ₹30-₹100 per subscription add up to ₹1,000-₹3,000 per year across multiple services.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is IDFC First WOW really zero forex and lifetime free?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, the IDFC First WOW Credit Card is confirmed zero forex markup and lifetime free with no conditions. It charges absolutely nothing for currency conversion on international transactions, has no joining fee, and no annual fee — ever. Additionally, it offers 6X reward points on travel, 3X on online shopping, 4 complimentary domestic lounge visits per year, and fuel surcharge waiver. It's widely regarded as the best value-for-money zero forex card in India. The only requirement is meeting IDFC First Bank's eligibility criteria (typically ₹15,000+ monthly income and 650+ CIBIL score).</div></div></div>
    </div>
